finding.triage_reasoning:
The implementation of `serializeAdapterCommand` (src/utils/type-guards.ts L137-140) is:
```ts
export function serializeAdapterCommand(cmd: AdapterCommand): string {
  validateAdapterCommand(cmd, 'serialization');
  return JSON.stringify(cmd);
}
```
It calls `validateAdapterCommand` (which calls `isValidAdapterCommand`) BEFORE calling `JSON.stringify`.

`isValidAdapterCommand` explicitly checks that all env values are strings:
```ts
for (const [key, value] of Object.entries(cmd.env)) {
  if (typeof key !== 'string' || typeof value !== 'string') {
    return false;
  }
}
```

A BigInt value like `{ BIG: BigInt(123) }` fails this check because `typeof BigInt(123) === 'bigint'`, not `'string'`. So `validateAdapterCommand` throws `"Invalid adapter command from serialization: ..."` — `JSON.stringify` is never reached.

The comment at L432 — "JSON.stringify will throw for BigInt before validation can catch it" — is factually wrong about the order of operations: validation runs first and catches BigInt env values. The test's `.toThrow('Do not know how to serialize a BigInt')` at L434 is also wrong for the same reason; if this test were actually run against the real implementation, it would fail because the thrown message would be "Invalid adapter command from serialization: ..." not the BigInt serialization error.

Note: the circular reference test at L421-423 correctly notes `JSON.stringify will throw TypeError`, because `{ cmd.circular = cmd }` passes `isValidAdapterCommand` (no env field, valid command and args), so validation succeeds and `JSON.stringify` is reached and throws. That comment is correct. Only the BigInt comment is wrong.

